{
  "card_id": "internal_structure",
  "type": "merged_concept",
  "canonical_term": "Internal Structure",
  "aliases": [],
  "school": "Smart Money Concepts (SMC)",
  "definition": "The price swings (highs and lows) that form within the range defined by the major external swing high and swing low. They represent minor price action and do not signal trend changes when broken.",
  "identification_rules": [
    "Identify the current major external high and low (the extremes that started and ended the impulsive wave); all subsequent swing points until a new external range is established are internal structures.",
    "A swing point is internal if it lies within the vertical price range of the established major high and low.",
    "If a price move breaks a swing high/low but does not meet the criteria for a valid BOS (e.g., candle body closes below the high with only a wick), the broken swing is an internal structure.",
    "Internal structures are not the extreme low/high that initiated the break of structure; that extreme becomes the major (external) level."
  ],
  "trading_implication": "Internal structure breaks are not trend reversal signals; they may represent inducement or minor pullbacks. Traders should wait for a confirmed break of a major (external) swing point to change bias. The internal price action within the external range is irrelevant to the market's bullish or bearish state as long as the extreme low/high holds.",
  "common_mistakes": [
    "Mistaking a break of an internal high/low for a valid break of structure (BOS) or trend reversal.",
    "Entering trades based on internal structure breaks without confirming a break of the major external level.",
    "Treating internal lows as major lows when they are not the extreme that initiated the BOS."
  ],
